text = "üïµÔ∏è DIGITAL DETECTIVE MANUAL

1. THE SENDER: Dont trust their names
The scammers can have acount names like some bank entity or famous subscription servie such as \"Netflix\". 
‚Ä¢ Lookup the domain: If the mail claims to be from Apple, but the email addres is [i]soporte@seguridad-cloud.com[/i], its a false email.
‚Ä¢ Take special care on fin details and typo: Make sure the email is [i]@mircosoft.com[/i] instead of somethings like this [i]@microsoft.com[/i].

2. TONE: Alarming and and rushing
If the message makes you nervous or frightened, ¬°STOP! 
‚Ä¢ Threats: \"Your account will be suspended in 2 hours\".
‚Ä¢ False Prices: \"You just won the latest Iphone!! Click here to claim it\".
They try to make you make the decisions on the rush of the rush of the moment, not by logical thinkig but by instinct or fear.

3. LINKS: The cursor trick
NEVER click a link without knowing what it leads to.
‚Ä¢ Hover the cursor over the link: In this game, if you hover the cursor over the link, you will see the real URL bellow. If the URL doesnt match the real one, ¬°RUN!
‚Ä¢ LINK SHORTERS: do not ever trust domains like bit.ly or others shorters as such even if the site name matches perfectly.

4. GREETINGS AND REDACTIONS:
‚Ä¢ Generics: \"Stimate client\" or \"Hello user\" are signs of danger. Real corporations usually know your name/username.
‚Ä¢ Errors: lookup for extrange translations or gramatical errors.

5. ATTACHED FILES
‚Ä¢ Strange extensions: Be carefull with .zip, .exe, or Taxe.pdf that you arent suposed to get or that you arent waiting for.

GOLDEN RULE: No real organization or company will ask you for personal data or passwords."

